# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acerum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe was created in the canton of Neuchâtel in Switzerland in the late 18th century by the French physician Pierre Ordinaire.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It rose to great popularity as an alcoholic drink in late 19th- and early 20th-century France, particularly among Parisian artists and writers.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The consumption of absinthe was opposed by social conservatives and prohibitionists, partly due to its association with bohemian culture.
[src:acerum/absinthe] From Europe and the Americas, notable absinthe drinkers included Ernest Hemingway, James Joyce, Lewis Carroll, Charles Baudelaire, Paul Verlaine, Arthur Rimbaud, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe has often been portrayed as a dangerously addictive psychoactive drug and hallucinogen, which gave birth to the term *absinthism*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The chemical compound thujone, which is present in the spirit in trace amounts, was blamed for its alleged harmful effects.
[src:acerum/absinthe] By 1915, absinthe had been banned in the United States and much of Europe, including France, the Netherlands, Belgium, Switzerland, and Austria-Hungary, though it has not been demonstrated to be any more dangerous than ordinary spirits.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Recent studies have shown that absinthe's psychoactive properties, apart from those attributable to its alcohol content, have been exaggerated.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe's revival began in the 1990s, following the adoption of modern European Union food and beverage laws that removed long-standing barriers to its production and sale.
[src:acerum/absinthe] By the early 21st century, nearly 200 brands of absinthe were being produced in a dozen countries, most notably in France, Switzerland, Austria, Germany, the Netherlands, Spain, and the Czech Republic.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The French word *absinthe* can refer either to the alcoholic beverage, or less commonly, to the actual wormwood plant.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe is derived from the Latin *absinthium*, which in turn comes from the Greek ἀψίνθιον *apsínthion* 'wormwood'.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some argue that the word means "undrinkable" in Greek, but it may instead be linked to the Persian root, in Persian called *spand* or *aspand* or the variant *esfand*, which meant *Peganum harmala*, also called Syrian rue in English, although it is not a variety of rue, another famously bitter herb.
[src:acerum/absinthe] That *Artemisia absinthium* was commonly burned as a protective offering may suggest that its origins lie in the reconstructed Proto-Indo-European language root **spend*, meaning "to perform a ritual" or "make an offering".
[src:acerum/absinthe] Whether the word was a borrowing from Persian into Greek, or from a common ancestor of both, is unclear.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Alternatively, the Greek word may originate in a pre-Greek substrate word, marked by the non-Indo-European consonant complex -νθ *-nth*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Alternative spellings for absinthe include *absinth*, *absynthe*, and *absenta*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] *Absinth* (without the final *e*) is a spelling variant most commonly applied to absinthes produced in central and eastern Europe, and is specifically associated with Bohemian-style absinthes.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The precise origin of absinthe is unclear.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The medical use of wormwood dates back to ancient Egypt and is mentioned in the Ebers Papyrus from around 1550 BC.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Wormwood extracts and wine-soaked wormwood leaves were used as remedies by the ancient Greeks.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Moreover, some evidence exists of a wormwood-flavoured wine in ancient Greece called *absinthites oinos*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Lucretius' *De Rerum Natura* (I, 936–950) says that a drink containing wormwood was given as medicine to children in a cup with honey on the brim to make it drinkable.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The first evidence of absinthe, in the sense of a distilled spirit containing green anise and fennel, dates to the 18th century.
[src:acerum/absinthe] According to popular legend, it began as an all-purpose patent remedy created by Dr.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Pierre Ordinaire, a French doctor living in Couvet, Switzerland, around 1792 (the exact date varies by account).
[src:acerum/absinthe] Ordinaire's recipe was passed on to the Henriod sisters of Couvet, who sold it as a medicinal elixir.
[src:acerum/absinthe] By other accounts, the Henriod sisters may have been making the elixir before Ordinaire's arrival.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In either case, a certain Major Dubied acquired the formula from the sisters in 1797 and opened the first absinthe distillery named Dubied Père et Fils in Couvet with his son Marcellin and son-in-law Henry-Louis Pernod.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 1805, they built a second distillery in Pontarlier, France, under the company name Maison Pernod Fils.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Pernod Fils remained one of the most popular brands of absinthe until the drink was banned in France in 1914.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe's popularity grew steadily through the 1840s, when it was given to French troops in Algeria as a malaria preventive, and the troops brought home their taste for it.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe became so popular in bars, bistros, cafés, and cabarets by the 1860s that the hour of 5 pm was called *l'heure verte* 'the green hour'.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was favoured by all social classes, from the wealthy bourgeoisie to poor artists and ordinary working-class people.
[src:acerum/absinthe] By the 1880s, mass production had caused the price to drop sharply, and the French were drinking 36 million litres (9,500,000 US gal) per year by 1910.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe was exported widely from France and Switzerland and attained some degree of popularity in other countries, including Spain, the United Kingdom, the United States, and the Czech Republic.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was never banned in Spain or Portugal, and its production and consumption have never ceased.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It gained a temporary popularity spike during the early 20th century, corresponding with the Art Nouveau and Modernism aesthetic movements.
[src:acerum/absinthe] New Orleans has a cultural association with absinthe and is credited as the birthplace of the Sazerac, perhaps the earliest absinthe cocktail.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The Old Absinthe House bar on Bourbon Street began selling absinthe in the first half of the 19th century.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Its Catalan lease-holder, Cayetano Ferrer, named it the Absinthe Room in 1874 due to the drink's popularity, which was served in the Parisian style.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was frequented by Mark Twain, Oscar Wilde, Franklin Delano Roosevelt, Aleister Crowley, and Frank Sinatra.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe became associated with violent crimes and social disorder, and one modern writer claims that this trend was spurred by fabricated claims and smear campaigns, which he claims were orchestrated by the temperance movement and the wine industry.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Edgar Degas's 1876 painting **The Absinthe Drinker** or **Glass of Absinthe** (**L'Absinthe**) can be seen at the Musée d'Orsay epitomising the popular view of absinthe addicts as sodden and benumbed, and Émile Zola described its effects in his novel *L'Assommoir*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 1905, Swiss farmer Jean Lanfray murdered his wife and two children and then attempted to kill himself after drinking absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Lanfray had drunk a lot of wine and brandy before the killings, but that was overlooked or ignored, and blame for the murders was placed solely on his consumption of two glasses of absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The Lanfray murders were the tipping point in this hotly debated topic, and a subsequent petition collected more than 82,000 signatures to ban it in Switzerland.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was approved by voters, and the prohibition of absinthe was written into the Swiss constitution.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 1906, Belgium and Brazil banned the sale and distribution of absinthe although these were not the first countries to take such action.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It had been banned as early as 1898 in the colony of the Congo Free State.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The Netherlands banned it in 1909, Switzerland in 1910, the United States in 1912, and France in 1914.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The prohibition of absinthe in France eventually led to the popularity of pastis, and to a lesser extent, ouzo, and other anise-flavoured spirits that do not contain wormwood.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Following the conclusion of the First World War, production of the Pernod Fils brand was resumed at the Banus distillery in Catalonia, Spain (where absinthe was still legal), but gradually declining sales saw the cessation of production in the 1960s.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Switzerland, the ban served only to drive the production of absinthe underground.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Clandestine home distillers produced colourless absinthe (*la Bleue*), which was easier to conceal from the authorities.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many countries never banned absinthe, notably the United Kingdom, where it had never been as popular as in continental Europe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] British importer BBH Spirits began to import Hill's Absinth from the Czech Republic in the 1990s, as the UK had never formally banned it, and this sparked a modern resurgence in its popularity.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It began to reappear during a revival in the 1990s in countries where it was never banned.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Forms of absinthe available during that time consisted almost exclusively of Czech, Spanish, and Portuguese brands that were of recent origin, typically consisting of Bohemian-style products.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Connoisseurs considered these of inferior quality and not representative of the 19th-century spirit.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2000, La Fée Absinthe became the first commercial absinthe distilled and bottled in France since the 1914 ban, but it is now one of dozens of brands that are produced and sold within France.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In the Netherlands, the restrictions were challenged by Amsterdam wine seller Menno Boorsma in July 2004, thus confirming the legality of absinthe once again.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Similarly, Belgium lifted its long-standing ban on 1 January 2005 citing a conflict with the adopted food and beverage regulations of the single European Market.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Switzerland, the constitutional ban was repealed in 2000 during an overhaul of the national constitution although the prohibition was written into ordinary law instead.
[src:acerum/absinthe] That law was later repealed, and absinthe was made legal on March 1, 2005.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The drink was never officially banned in Spain although it began to fall out of favour in the 1940s and almost vanished into obscurity.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Catalonia has seen a significant resurgence since 2007 when one producer established operations there.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe has never been illegal to import or manufacture in Australia although importation requires a permit under the Customs (Prohibited Imports) Regulation 1956 due to a restriction on importing any product containing oil of wormwood.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2000, an amendment made all wormwood species prohibited herbs for food purposes under Food Standard 1.4.4.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Prohibited and Restricted Plants and Fungi.
[src:acerum/absinthe] However, this amendment was found inconsistent with other parts of the pre-existing Food Code, and it was withdrawn in 2002 during the transition between the two codes, thereby continuing to allow absinthe manufacture and importation through the existing permit-based system.
[src:acerum/absinthe] These events were erroneously reported by the media as it having been reclassified from a *prohibited* product to a *restricted* product.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2007, the French brand Lucid became the first genuine absinthe to receive a Certificate of Label Approval for import into the United States since 1912, following independent efforts by representatives from Lucid and Kübler to overturn the long-standing U.S. ban.
[src:acerum/absinthe] George Spirits of Alameda, California became the first brand of American-made absinthe produced in the United States since the ban.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Since that time, other micro-distilleries have started producing small batches in the United States.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The French Absinthe Ban of 1915 was repealed in May 2011 following petitions by the *Fédération Française des Spiritueux*, which represents French distillers, and the French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in April 2011.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Switzerland, the village of Môtiers, Val-de-Travers, near Neuchâtel, became the focal point of production and promotion of the liquor after a ban of nearly 100 years was lifted.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The national *Maison de l'Absinthe* (House of Absinthe), with its attached museum, is located in the former courthouse where absinthe distillers were formerly prosecuted.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The 21st century has seen new types of absinthe, including various frozen preparations, that have become increasingly popular.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Most countries have no legal definition for absinthe, whereas the method of production and content of spirits such as whisky, brandy, and gin are globally defined and regulated.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Therefore, producers are at liberty to label a product as "absinthe" or "absinth" without regard to any specific legal definition or quality standards.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Producers of legitimate absinthes employ one of two historically defined processes to create the finished spirit – distillation or cold mixing.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In the sole country (Switzerland) that does possess a legal definition of absinthe, distillation is the only permitted method of production.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Distilled absinthe employs a method of production similar to that of high-quality gin.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Botanicals are initially macerated in distilled base alcohol before being redistilled to exclude bitter principles, and impart the desired complexity and texture to the spirit.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The distillation of absinthe first yields a colourless distillate that leaves the alembic at around 72% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The distillate may be reduced and bottled clear, to produce a *Blanche* or *la Bleue* absinthe, or it may be coloured to create a *verte* using natural or artificial colouring.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Traditional absinthes obtain their green color strictly from the chlorophyll of whole herbs, which is extracted from the plants during the secondary maceration.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This step involves steeping plants such as petite wormwood, hyssop, and melissa (among other herbs) in the distillate.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Chlorophyll from these herbs is extracted, giving the drink its famous green color.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This step also provides a herbal complexity that is typical of high-quality absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The natural coloring process is critical for absinthe ageing since the chlorophyll remains chemically active.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The chlorophyll serves a similar role in absinthe as tannins do in wine or brown liquors.
[src:acerum/absinthe] After the coloring process, the resulting product is diluted with water to the desired alcohol percentage.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The flavor of absinthe is said to improve materially with storage, and many distilleries, before the ban, aged their absinthe in settling tanks before bottling.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many modern absinthes are produced using a cold-mix process.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This inexpensive method of production does not involve distillation, and is regarded as inferior for the same reasons that give cause for cheaply compounded gin to be legally differentiated from distilled gin.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The cold mixing process involves the simple blending of flavouring essences and artificial colouring in commercial alcohol, in similar fashion to most flavoured vodkas and inexpensive liqueurs and cordials.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some modern cold-mixed absinthes have been bottled at strengths approaching 90% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Others are presented simply as a bottle of plain alcohol with a small amount of powdered herbs suspended within it.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The lack of a formal legal definition in most countries to regulate the production and quality of absinthe has enabled cheaply made products to be falsely presented as traditional in production and composition.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Switzerland, the only country with a formal legal definition of absinthe, any absinthe product not obtained by maceration and distillation or coloured artificially cannot be sold as absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe is traditionally prepared from a distillation of neutral alcohol, various herbs, spices, and water.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Traditional absinthes were redistilled from a white grape spirit (or *eau de vie*), while lesser absinthes were more commonly made from alcohol from grains, beets, or potatoes.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The principal botanicals are grande wormwood, green anise, and florence fennel, which are often called "the holy trinity".
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many other herbs may be used as well, such as petite wormwood (*Artemisia pontica* or Roman wormwood), hyssop, melissa, star anise, angelica, peppermint, coriander, and veronica.
[src:acerum/absinthe] One early recipe was included in 1864's *The English and Australian Cookery Book*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It directed the maker to "Take of the tops of wormwood, four pounds; root of angelica, calamus aromaticus, aniseed, leaves of dittany, of each one ounce; alcohol, four gallons.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Macerate these substances during eight days, add a little water, and distil by a gentle fire, until two gallons are obtained.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Adding to absinthe's negative reputation in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, unscrupulous makers of the drink omitted the traditional colouring phase of production in favour of adding toxic copper salts to artificially induce a green tint.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This practice may be responsible for some of the alleged toxicity historically associated with this beverage.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many modern-day producers resort to other shortcuts, including the use of artificial food coloring to create the green color.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Additionally, at least some cheap absinthes produced before the ban were reportedly adulterated with poisonous antimony trichloride, reputed to enhance the louching effect.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe may also be naturally coloured pink or red using rose or hibiscus flowers.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This was referred to as a *rose* (pink) or *rouge* (red) absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Only one historical brand of rose absinthe has been documented.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe was historically bottled at 45–74% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some modern Franco–Suisse absinthes are bottled at up to 83% ABV, while some modern, cold-mixed bohemian-style absinthes are bottled at up to 89.9% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The modern-day interest in absinthe has spawned a rash of absinthe kits from sellers claiming they produce homemade absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Kits often call for soaking herbs in vodka or alcohol or adding a liquid concentrate to vodka or alcohol to create an ersatz absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Such practices usually yield a harsh substance that bears little resemblance to the genuine article and is considered inauthentic by any practical standard.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some concoctions may even be dangerous, especially if they call for a potentially poisonous inclusion of herbs, oils, or extracts.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In at least one documented case, a person suffered acute kidney injury after drinking 10 ml of pure wormwood oil.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In baking and in preparing the classic New Orleans-style Sazerac cocktail, anise-flavored liqueurs and pastis have often been used as a substitute if absinthe is unavailable.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The traditional French preparation involves placing a sugar cube on top of a specially designed slotted spoon and placing the spoon on a glass filled with a measure of absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Iced water is poured or dripped over the sugar cube to mix the water into the absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The final preparation contains 1 part absinthe and 3–5 parts water.
[src:acerum/absinthe] As water dilutes the spirit, those components with poor water solubility (mainly those from anise, fennel, and star anise) come out of solution and cloud the drink.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The resulting milky opalescence is called the *louche* (/luʃ/, French: 'opaque' or 'shady').
[src:acerum/absinthe] The release of these dissolved essences coincides with a perfuming of herbal aromas and flavours that "blossom" or "bloom", and brings out subtleties that are otherwise muted within the neat spirit.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This reflects what is perhaps the oldest and purest method of preparation, and is often referred to as the *French method*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The *Bohemian method* is a recent invention that involves fire, and was not performed during absinthe's peak of popularity in the Belle Époque.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Like the French method, a sugar cube is placed on a slotted spoon over a glass containing one shot of absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The sugar is soaked in alcohol (usually more absinthe), and then set ablaze.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The flaming sugar cube is then dropped into the glass, thus igniting the absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Finally, a shot glass of water is added to douse the flames.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This method tends to produce a stronger drink than the French method.
[src:acerum/absinthe] A variant of the Bohemian method involves allowing the fire to extinguish on its own.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This variant is sometimes referred to as "cooking the absinthe" or "the flaming green fairy".
[src:acerum/absinthe] The origin of this burning ritual may borrow from a coffee and brandy drink that was served at Café Brûlot, in which a sugar cube soaked in brandy was set aflame.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Most experienced absintheurs do not recommend the Bohemian Method and consider it a modern gimmick, as it can destroy the absinthe flavour and present a fire hazard due to the unusually high alcohol content present in absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 19th-century Parisian cafés, upon receiving an order for absinthe, a waiter would present the patron with a dose of absinthe in a suitable glass, sugar, absinthe spoon, and a carafe of iced water.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was up to the patron to prepare the drink, as the inclusion or omission of sugar was strictly an individual preference, as was the amount of water used.
[src:acerum/absinthe] As the popularity of the drink increased, additional accoutrements of preparation appeared, including the absinthe fountain, which was effectively a large jar of iced water with spigots, mounted on a lamp base.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This lets drinkers prepare several drinks at once – and with a hands-free drip, patrons could socialise while louching a glass.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Although many bars served absinthe in standard glassware, several glasses were specifically designed for the French absinthe preparation ritual.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe glasses were typically fashioned with a dose line, bulge, or bubble in the lower portion denoting how much absinthe should be poured.
[src:acerum/absinthe] One "dose" of absinthe ranged anywhere around 2–2.5 fluid ounces (60–75 ml).
[src:acerum/absinthe] In addition to being prepared with sugar and water, absinthe emerged as a popular cocktail ingredient in both the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:acerum/absinthe] By 1930, dozens of fancy cocktails that called for absinthe had been published in numerous credible bartender guides.
[src:acerum/absinthe] One of the most famous of these libations is Ernest Hemingway's "Death in the Afternoon" cocktail, a tongue-in-cheek concoction that contributed to a 1935 collection of celebrity recipes.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The directions are: "Pour one jigger absinthe into a Champagne glass.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Add iced Champagne until it attains the proper opalescent milkiness.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Most categorical alcoholic beverages have regulations governing their classification and labelling, while those governing absinthe have always been conspicuously lacking.
[src:acerum/absinthe] According to popular treatises from the 19th century, absinthe could be loosely categorised into several grades (*ordinaire*, *demi-fine*, *fine*, and *Suisse* – the latter does not denote origin), in order of increasing alcoholic strength and quality.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many contemporary absinthe critics simply classify absinthe as *distilled* or *mixed*, according to its production method.
[src:acerum/absinthe] And while the former is generally considered far superior in quality to the latter, an absinthe's simple claim of being 'distilled' makes no guarantee as to the quality of its base ingredients or the skill of its maker.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe that is artificially coloured or clear is aesthetically stable and can be bottled in clear glass.
[src:acerum/absinthe] If naturally colored absinthe is exposed to light or air for a prolonged period, the chlorophyll gradually becomes oxidized, which has the effect of gradually changing the color from green to yellow green, and eventually to brown.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The colour of absinthe that has completed this transition was historically referred to as *feuille morte* ("dead leaf").
[src:acerum/absinthe] In the pre-ban era, this natural phenomenon was favourably viewed, for it confirmed the product in question was coloured naturally, and not artificially with potentially toxic chemicals.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Predictably, vintage absinthes often emerge from sealed bottles as distinctly amber in tint due to decades of slow oxidation.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Though this colour change presents no adverse impact to the flavour of absinthe, it is generally desired to preserve the original colour, which requires that naturally coloured absinthe be bottled in dark, light-resistant bottles.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe intended for decades of storage should be kept in a cool (room temperature), dry place, away from light and heat.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe should not be stored in the refrigerator or freezer, as the anethole may polymerise inside the bottle, creating an irreversible precipitate, and adversely impacting the original flavour.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe has been frequently described in modern times as being hallucinogenic, a claim refuted by modern science.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The belief that absinthe induces hallucinogenic effects is rooted, at least partly, in the findings of 19th-century French psychiatrist Valentin Magnan, who carried out ten years of experiments with wormwood oil.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In the course of this research, he studied 250 cases of alcoholism and concluded that those who abused absinthe were worse off than those who abused other alcoholic drinks, experiencing rapid-onset hallucinations.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Such accounts by opponents of absinthe (like Magnan) were cheerfully embraced by famous absinthe drinkers, many of whom were bohemian artists or writers.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Two famous artists who helped popularise the notion that absinthe had powerful psychoactive properties were Toulouse-Lautrec and Vincent van Gogh.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In one of the best-known written accounts of absinthe drinking, an inebriated Oscar Wilde described a phantom sensation of having tulips brush against his legs after leaving a bar at closing time.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Notions of absinthe's alleged hallucinogenic properties were again fuelled in the 1970s when a scientific paper suggested that thujone's structural similarity to tetrahydrocannabinol (THC), the active chemical in cannabis, presented the possibility of THC receptor affinity.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Counterevidence to this was published in 1999.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The debate over whether absinthe produces effects on the human mind in addition to those of alcohol has not been resolved conclusively.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The effects of absinthe have been described by some as mind-opening.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The most commonly reported experience is a "clear-headed" feeling of inebriation – a form of "lucid drunkenness".
[src:acerum/absinthe] Chemist, historian, and absinthe distiller Ted Breaux has claimed that the alleged secondary effects of absinthe may be because some of the herbal compounds in the drink act as stimulants, while others act as sedatives, creating an overall lucid effect of awakening.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The long-term effects of moderate absinthe consumption in humans remain unknown, although herbs traditionally used to produce absinthe are reported to have both painkilling and antiparasitic properties.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Today it is known that absinthe does not cause hallucinations.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It was once widely promoted that excessive absinthe drinking caused effects that were discernible from those associated with alcoholism, a belief that led to the coining of the term *absinthism*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] One of the first vilifications of absinthe followed an 1864 experiment in which Magnan simultaneously exposed one guinea pig to large doses of pure wormwood vapour, and another to alcohol vapours.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The guinea pig exposed to wormwood vapour experienced convulsive seizures, while the animal exposed to alcohol did not.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Magnan would later blame the naturally occurring (in wormwood) chemical thujone for these effects.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Thujone, once widely believed to be an active chemical in absinthe, is a GABA antagonist, and while it can produce muscle spasms in large doses, there is no direct evidence to suggest it causes hallucinations.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Past reports estimated thujone concentrations in absinthe as being up to 260 mg/kg.
[src:acerum/absinthe] As such, most traditionally crafted absinthes, both vintage and modern, fall within the current EU standards.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Tests conducted on mice to study toxicity showed an oral LD50 of about 45 mg thujone per kg of body weight, which represents far more absinthe than could be realistically consumed.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The high percentage of alcohol in absinthe would result in mortality long before thujone could become a factor.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In documented cases of acute thujone poisoning as a result of oral ingestion, the source of thujone was not commercial absinthe, but rather non-absinthe-related sources, such as common essential oils (which may contain as much as 50% thujone).
[src:acerum/absinthe] One study published in the *Journal of Studies on Alcohol* concluded that high doses (0.28 mg/kg) of thujone in alcohol had negative effects on attention performance in a clinical setting.
[src:acerum/absinthe] It delayed reaction time, and caused subjects to concentrate their attention on the central field of vision.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Low doses (0.028 mg/kg) did not produce an effect noticeably different from the plain alcohol control.
[src:acerum/absinthe] While the effects of the high dose samples were statistically significant in a double blind test, the test subjects themselves were unable to reliably identify which samples contained thujone.
[src:acerum/absinthe] For the average 65 kg (143 lb) man, the high dose samples in the study would equate to 18.2 mg of thujone.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The EU limit of 35 mg/L of thujone in absinthe means that given the highest permitted thujone content, that individual would need to consume approximately 0.5 litres of high-proof (e.g.
[src:acerum/absinthe] 50%+ ABV) spirit before the thujone could be metabolized to display effects detectable in a clinical setting, which would result in a potentially lethal BAC of >0.4%.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Most countries (except Switzerland) at present do not possess a legal definition of absinthe (unlike Scotch whisky or cognac).
[src:acerum/absinthe] Accordingly, producers are free to label a product "absinthe" or "absinth", whether or not it bears any resemblance to the traditional spirit.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe is readily available in many bottle shops.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Bitters may contain a maximum 35 mg/kg thujone, while other alcoholic beverages can contain a maximum 10 mg/kg.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The domestic production and sale of absinthe is regulated by state licensing laws.
[src:acerum/absinthe] These controls have now been repealed, and permission is no longer required.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe was prohibited in Brazil until 1999 and was brought by entrepreneur Lalo Zanini and legalised in the same year.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Presently, absinthe sold in Brazil must abide by the national law that restricts all spirits to a maximum of 54% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] While this regulation is enforced throughout channels of legal distribution, it may be possible to find absinthe containing alcohol in excess of the legal limit in some restaurants or food fairs.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Canada, liquor laws concerning the production, distribution, and sale of spirits are written and enforced by individual provincial government monopolies.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Each product is subject to the approval of a respective individual provincial liquor board before it can be sold in that province.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Importation is a federal matter and is enforced by the Canada Border Services Agency.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The importation of a nominal amount of liquor by individuals for personal use is permitted, provided that conditions for the individual's duration of stay outside the country are satisfied.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2007, Canada's first genuine absinthe (Taboo Absinthe) was created by Okanagan Spirits Craft Distillery in British Columbia.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The European Union permits a maximum thujone level of 35 mg/kg in alcoholic beverages where *Artemisia* species is a listed ingredient, and 10 mg/kg in other alcoholic beverages.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Member countries regulate absinthe production within this framework.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The sale of absinthe is permitted in all EU countries unless they further regulate it.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe was prohibited in Finland from 1919 to 1932; no current prohibitions exist.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The government-owned chain of liquor stores (Alko) is the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing over 8% ABV, although national law bans the sale of alcoholic beverages containing over 80% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Édouard Manet's first major painting *The Absinthe Drinker* was controversial, and was rejected by the Paris Salon in 1859.
[src:acerum/absinthe] French producers circumvented this regulatory obstacle by labelling absinthe as *spiritueux à base de plantes d'absinthe* ('wormwood-based spirits'), with many either reducing or omitting fennel and hyssop altogether from their products.
[src:acerum/absinthe] A legal challenge to the scientific basis of this decree resulted in its repeal (2009), which opened the door for the official French re-legalisation of absinthe for the first time since 1915.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The French Senate voted to repeal the prohibition in mid-April 2011.
[src:acerum/absinthe] A ban on absinthe was enacted in Germany on 27 March 1923.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In addition to banning the production of commercial trade in absinthe, the law went so far as to prohibit the distribution of printed matter that provided details of its production.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The original ban was lifted in 1981, but the use of *Artemisia absinthium* as a flavouring agent remained prohibited.
[src:acerum/absinthe] On 27 September 1991, Germany adopted the European Community's standards of 1988, which effectively re-legalised absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The Fascist regime in 1926 banned the production, import, transport, and sale of any liquor named *Assenzio*.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The ban was reinforced in 1931 with harsher penalties for transgressors and remained in force until 1992 when the Italian government amended its laws to comply with the EU directive 88/388/EEC.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Although absinthe is not prohibited at the national level, some local authorities have banned it.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The ban came in August 2008 after several issues of misuse drew public and police attention.
[src:acerum/absinthe] One incident resulted in breathing difficulties and hospitalising of a 17-year-old for alcohol poisoning.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The particular brand of absinthe that caused these effects was bottled at 89% ABV.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The sale and production of absinthe has never been prohibited in Sweden or Norway.
[src:acerum/absinthe] However, the only outlet that may sell alcoholic beverages containing more than 3.5% ABV in Sweden and 4.75% ABV in Norway is the government-owned chain of liquor stores known as Systembolaget in Sweden and Vinmonopolet in Norway.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Systembolaget and Vinmonopolet did not import or sell absinthe for many years after the ban in France; however, today several absinthes are available for purchase in Systembolaget stores, including Swedish made distilled absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Norway, on the other hand, one is less likely to find many absinthes since Norwegian alcohol law prohibits the sale and importation of alcoholic beverages above 60% ABV, which eliminates most absinthes.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In Switzerland, the sale and production of absinthe was prohibited from 1910 to 1 March 2005.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This was based on a vote in 1908, inspired by the Jean Lanfray incident.
[src:acerum/absinthe] To be legally made or sold in Switzerland, absinthe must be distilled, must not contain certain additives, and must be either naturally coloured or left uncoloured.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2014, the Federal Administrative Court of Switzerland invalidated a governmental decision of 2010 which allowed only absinthe made in the Val-de-Travers region to be labelled as absinthe in Switzerland.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The court found that absinthe was a label for a product and was not tied to a geographic origin.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe was never legally prohibited in the UK, but was not imported for a 70-year period.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In 2007, the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau (TTB) effectively lifted the long-standing absinthe ban, and it has since approved many brands for sale in the US market.
[src:acerum/absinthe] This was made possible partly through the TTB's clarification of the Food and Drug Administration's (FDA) thujone content regulations, which specify that finished food and beverages that contain *Artemisia* species must be thujone-free.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In this context, the TTB considers a product thujone-free if the thujone content is less than 10 ppm (equal to 10 mg/kg).
[src:acerum/absinthe] This is verified through the use of gas chromatography–mass spectrometry.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The brands Kübler and Lucid and their lawyers did most of the work to get absinthe legalized in the U.S., over the 2004–2007 time period.
[src:acerum/absinthe] In the U.S., 5 March sometimes is referred to as "National Absinthe Day", as it was the day the 95-year ban on absinthe was finally lifted.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Absinthe imported in violation of these regulations is subject to seizure at the discretion of U.S.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Numerous artists and writers living in France in the late 19th and early 20th centuries were noted absinthe drinkers and featured absinthe in their work.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some of these included Édouard Manet, Guy de Maupassant, Paul Verlaine, Amedeo Modigliani, Edgar Degas, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Vincent van Gogh, Oscar Wilde, Arthur Rimbaud, and Émile Zola.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Many other renowned artists and writers similarly drew from this cultural well, including Aleister Crowley, Ernest Hemingway, Pablo Picasso, August Strindberg, and Erik Satie.
[src:acerum/absinthe] The aura of illicitness and mystery surrounding absinthe has played into literature, movies, music, and television, where it is often portrayed as a mysterious, addictive, and mind-altering drink.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Marie Corelli's *Wormwood: A Drama of Paris* (1890) was a popular novel about a Frenchman driven to murder and ruin after being introduced to absinthe.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Intended as a morality tale on the dangers of the drink, it was speculated to have contributed to subsequent bans of absinthe in Europe and the United States.
[src:acerum/absinthe] Some of the earliest film references include *The Hasher's Delirium* (1910) by Émile Cohl, an early pioneer in the art of animation, as well as two different silent films, each titled *Absinthe*, from 1913 and 1914 respectively.
[src:acerum/absinthe] More recently, it served as the title of a 2018 song by the indie group I Don't Know How But They Found Me.
[src:acerum/acerum] In the 1970s, distillers began to produce alcohol from maple syrup.
[src:acerum/acerum] Although some distilled alcohol tests were then carried out in university laboratories, it was not until the 1990s that certain maple syrup producers began to produce a wine based on this sweet resource, which was initially called Acer.
[src:acerum/acerum] One of the first producers of Acerum was The Domaine Acer, based in Témiscouata, Quebec.
[src:acerum/acerum] When Vallier Robert took the reins of his family maple business in 1990, he quickly saw the potential to make alcohol.
[src:acerum/acerum] In 1996, the maple farmer was granted the first licence to produce artisanal maple-based alcoholic beverages.
[src:acerum/acerum] He began creating several varieties of maple sap wine, including dry, sparkling and dessert wines.
[src:acerum/acerum] During the same period, some distilleries began to market maple eau-de-vie, but it was not until December 2017 that the name Acerum appeared for the first time for a maple eau-de-vie.
[src:acerum/acerum] As defined by the specifications of the UDSÉ, Acerum must be entirely manufactured in the province of Quebec, in Canada, with maple syrup, maple concentrate, or maple sap from Quebec maples.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Two theories have been put out on the origins of "advocaat".
[src:acerum/advocaat] According to several makers, such as Verpoorten and Bols, and the *Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets*, its origins can be traced back to "abacate", an alcoholic beverage of the indigenous people in Brazil, which was made with avocado.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Dutch colonials of northern Brazil introduced this beverage to Europe as "advocat/advocaat".
[src:acerum/advocaat] As avocados could not grow in northern Europe, they were replaced with egg yolk, thought to have a similar taste and consistency, and the name derived from the avocado stuck, although the drink no longer contains any.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Cooymans started a distillery in downtown 's-Hertogenbosch.
[src:acerum/advocaat] There he developed the egg drink "advocaat".
[src:acerum/advocaat] In 1876, the Antwerp distiller Eugen Verpoorten established a distillery in Heinsberg near Aachen, Germany, which made an egg liqueur (*Eierlikör* in German) using eggs, sugar, distilled alcohol, and other ingredients.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Jars and wide mouth bottles of thick advocaat are sold mainly in the Netherlands and Belgium, though may be available in Germany, Austria, and South Africa.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Further exports are of a more liquid version.
[src:acerum/advocaat] In particular the original thick variety, i.e., without albumen, is used as a waffle, pancake or poffertjes topping, as an ingredient in ice cream, custards, pastries and similar desserts, or as an apéritif or digestif.
[src:acerum/advocaat] The latter, possibly topped with whipped cream and then occasionally sprinkled with a touch of cocoa powder, is served in a very tiny bowl or small glass from which it is eaten by use of a teaspoon.
[src:acerum/advocaat] In Belgian restaurants and taverns, it may be a complementary accompaniment to a coffee.
[src:acerum/advocaat] In the export variety both parts of the eggs are used.
[src:acerum/advocaat] A popular cocktail using advocaat is the Snowball: a mixture of advocaat, sparkling lemonade and sometimes (although this is not required) lime juice that is often consumed at Christmas time.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Another is the Fluffy duck, made with rum.
[src:acerum/advocaat] Another advocaat-based beverage is the Bombardino, a drink commonly found in Italian ski resorts, particularly the Italian Alps, made by mixing advocaat, brandy, and whipped cream.
[src:acerum/advocaat] The Polish equivalent, *ajerkoniak* (German: *eier* 'eggs' and French: *cognac*), is based on vodka instead of brandy, despite what the name may suggest.
[src:acerum/agave] Many plants in this genus may be considered perennial, because they require several to many years to mature and flower.
[src:acerum/agave] However, most *Agave* species are more accurately described as monocarpic rosettes or multiannuals, since each individual rosette flowers only once and then dies; a small number of *Agave* species are polycarpic.
[src:acerum/agave] Along with plants from the closely related genera *Yucca*, *Hesperoyucca*, and *Hesperaloe,* various *Agave* species are popular ornamental plants in hot, dry climates, as they require very little supplemental water to survive.
[src:acerum/agave] Some *Agave* species are known by the common name "century plant".
[src:acerum/agave] In other regions, it goes by different names.
[src:acerum/agave] In the Chinese, Japanese, and Korean languages, it is referred to as the compound word *dragon tongue orchid* (simplified Chinese: 龙舌兰; traditional Chinese: 龍舌蘭; pinyin: *lóngshélán*; Japanese: 竜舌蘭, romanized: *ryūzetsuran*; Korean: 용설란; Hanja: 龍舌蘭; RR: *yongseollan*).
[src:acerum/agave] In Malta, it is referred to as *Sabbara*; In Maltese, Agave americana is referred to as "Sabbara tal-Amerika", and Agave sisalana is referred to as "Sabbara ta' Sisal".
[src:acerum/agave] The succulent leaves of most *Agave* species have sharp marginal teeth, an extremely sharp terminal spine, and are very fibrous inside.
[src:acerum/agave] The stout stem is usually extremely short, which may make the plant appear as though it is stemless.
[src:acerum/agave] Agaves can be confused with cacti, aloes, or stonecrops, but although these plants all share similar morphological adaptations to arid environments (e.g. succulence), each group belongs to a different plant family and probably experienced convergent evolution.
[src:acerum/agave] Further, cactus (Cactaceae) and stonecrop (Crassulaceae) lineages are eudicots, while aloes (Asphodelaceae) and agaves (Asparagaceae) are monocots.
[src:acerum/agave] The agave root system, consisting of a network of shallow rhizomes, allows the agave to efficiently capture moisture from rain, condensation, and dew.
[src:acerum/agave] In addition to growing from seeds, most agaves produce 'pups' – young plants from runners.
[src:acerum/agave] *Agave vilmoriniana* (the octopus agave) produces hundreds of pups on its bloom stalk.
[src:acerum/agave] Agave leaves store the plant's water and are crucial to its continued existence.
[src:acerum/agave] The coated leaf surface prevents evaporation.
[src:acerum/agave] The leaves also have sharp, spiked edges.
[src:acerum/agave] The spikes discourage predators from eating the plant or using it as a source of water and are so tough that ancient peoples used them for sewing needles.
[src:acerum/agave] Some agaves bloom at a height up to 9 m (30 ft) so that they are far out of reach to animals that might attack them.
[src:acerum/agave] Smaller species, such as *Agave lechuguilla*, have smaller bloom stalks.
[src:acerum/agave] The genus name *Agave* come from the Ancient Greek αγαυή *agauê* from ἀγαυός *agauós* meaning "illustrious, noble" having to do with very tall flower spikes found on its many species.
[src:acerum/agave] The genus *Agave* was erected by Carl Linnaeus in 1753, initially with four species.
[src:acerum/agave] The first listed was *Agave americana*, now the type species.
[src:acerum/agave] In the Cronquist system and others, *Agave* was placed in the family Liliaceae, but phylogenetic analyses of DNA sequences later showed it did not belong there.
[src:acerum/agave] In the APG II system, *Agave* was placed in the segregated family Agavaceae.
[src:acerum/agave] When this system was superseded by the APG III system in 2009, the Agavaceae were subsumed into the expanded family Asparagaceae, and *Agave* was treated as one of 18 genera in the subfamily Agavoideae, a position retained in the APG IV system of 2016.
[src:acerum/agave] However, Agavaceae had regained its taxonomic status as an independent family by 2020.
[src:acerum/agave] Agaves and close relatives have long presented significant taxonomic difficulty.
[src:acerum/agave] These difficulties could be due to the relatively young evolutionary age of the group (major diversification events of the group most likely occurred 8–10 million years ago), ease of hybridization between species (and even genera), incomplete lineage sorting, and long generation times.
[src:acerum/agave] Within a species, morphological variations can be considerable, especially in cultivation; many named species may be variants of original wild-type species that horticulturalists bred to appear unique in cultivation.
[src:acerum/agave] With the advent of DNA sequencing, new karyologic and evolutionary phylogenetic studies showed that the genera *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* were genetically nested within the traditional circumscription of *Agave*, rendering the genus paraphyletic.
[src:acerum/agave] Early in the 21st century, these new phylogenetic results led to a reclassification of to include *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes* together as *Agave* subgenus *Manfreda*.
[src:acerum/agave] There was reaction against the changes from those who noted that the large morphological differences between the genera in this new *Agave* s.l. making them "counter-intuitive from a horticultural point of view".
[src:acerum/agave] *Manfreda* morphologically differs from the classic *Agave* description in being herbaceous and bulbous, while *Polianthes* are deciduous with narrow leaves and no spines.
[src:acerum/agave] Mexican taxonomists have continued to adhere to the traditional classifications and have published new species of *Polianthes*.
[src:acerum/agave] Thus, based on a wider consideration of previously established genetic, morphological, and estimated genetic divergence times, Vázquez-García et al. proposed a narrower circumscription of *Agave* by creating three new genera: *Echinoagave*, *Paleoagave* and *Paraagave*.
[src:acerum/agave] These new genera have gained some acceptance, and pave the way for a reconsideration of *Manfreda*, *Polianthes* and *Prochnyanthes*.
[src:acerum/agave] Some commonly grown species include *Agave americana*, *A. angustifolia*, *A. attenuata*, *A. murpheyi*, *A. palmeri*, *A. parryi*, *A. parviflora*, *A. tequilana*, *A. victoriae-reginae*, and *A. vilmoriniana*.
[src:acerum/agave] One of the most familiar species is *A. americana*, a native of tropical America.
[src:acerum/agave] Common names include century plant, *maguey* (in Mexico), or American aloe (though not related to the genus *Aloe*).
[src:acerum/agave] The name "century plant" refers to the long time the plant takes to flower.
[src:acerum/agave] The number of years before flowering occurs depends on the vigor of the individual plant, the richness of the soil, and the climate; during these years, the plant is storing in its fleshy leaves the nourishment required for the effort of flowering.
[src:acerum/agave] Some species contain components in their juice which can cause dermatitis for some people.
[src:acerum/agave] The ethnobotany of the agave was described by William H.
[src:acerum/agave] The four major edible parts of the agave are the flowers, the leaves, the stalks or basal rosettes, and the sap (in Spanish: *aguamiel*, meaning "honey water").
[src:acerum/agave] The sap of some species can also be used as soap.
[src:acerum/agave] Each agave plant produces several pounds of edible flowers during its final season.
[src:acerum/agave] The stalks, which are ready during the summer, before the blossom, weigh several pounds each.
[src:acerum/agave] Roasted, they are sweet and can be chewed to extract the sap or *aguamiel*, like sugarcane.
[src:acerum/agave] When dried out, the stalks can be used to make didgeridoos.
[src:acerum/agave] The leaves may be collected in winter and spring, when the plants are rich in sap, for eating.
[src:acerum/agave] The leaves of several species also yield fiber, for instance, *A. sisalana*, the sisal hemp, and *A. decipiens*, the false sisal hemp.
[src:acerum/agave] *A. americana* is the source of pita fiber, and is used as a fiber plant in Mexico, the West Indies, and southern Europe.
[src:acerum/agave] The agave, especially *A. murpheyi*, was a major food source for the prehistoric indigenous people of the Southwestern United States.
[src:acerum/agave] The Hohokam of southern Arizona cultivated large areas of agave.
[src:acerum/agave] The Navajo similarly found many uses for the agave plant.
[src:acerum/agave] A beverage is squeezed from the baked fibers, and the heads can be baked or boiled, pounded into flat sheets, sun dried, and stored for future use.
[src:acerum/agave] The baked, dried heads are also boiled and made into an edible paste, eaten whole, or made into soup.
[src:acerum/agave] The leaves are eaten boiled, and the young, tender flowering stalks and shoots are roasted and eaten as well.
[src:acerum/agave] The fibers are used to make rope, the leaves are used to line baking pits, and the sharp-pointed leaf tips are used to make basketry awls.
[src:acerum/agave] During the development of the inflorescence, sap rushes to the base of the young flower stalk.
[src:acerum/agave] Agave syrup (commonly called agave nectar), a sweetener derived from the sap, is used as an alternative to sugar in cooking, and can be added to breakfast cereals as a binding agent.
[src:acerum/agave] Extracts from agave leaves are under preliminary research for their potential use as food additives.
[src:acerum/agave] The sap of *A. americana* and other species is used in Mexico and Mesoamerica to produce pulque, an alcoholic beverage.
[src:acerum/agave] The flower shoot is cut out and the sap collected and subsequently fermented.
[src:acerum/agave] By distillation, a spirit called mezcal is prepared; one of the best-known forms of mezcal is tequila.
[src:acerum/agave] *azul* is used in the production of tequila.
[src:acerum/agave] *A. angustifolia* is widely used in the production of mezcal and pulque, though at least 10 other *Agave* species are also known to be used for this.
[src:acerum/agave] Agave can be used as the raw material for industrial production of fructans as a prebiotic dietary fiber.
[src:acerum/agave] Agave contains fructooligosaccharides, which are naturally occurring oligosaccharides that support safely subjecting peanut-allergic people to allergen immunotherapy.
[src:acerum/agave] Resulting from its natural habitat in stressful environments, agave is under preliminary research for its potential use in germplasm conservation and in biotechnology to better anticipate the economic effects of global climate change.
[src:acerum/agave] It may also have use as a bioethanol or bioenergy feedstock.
[src:acerum/agave] Agave plantations have potential applications on marginal lands unsuitable for grain crops.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The word is a compound of the Iberian languages' words for 'water' (*agua* in Castilian, i.e.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Spanish; *aigua* in Catalan; *água* in Portuguese; *auga* in Galician) and 'burning'/'fiery' (*ardiente* in Castilian; *ardent* in Catalan; *ardente* in Portuguese and Galician).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] A comparable word in English is "firewater", though the English term is colloquial or humorous, whereas *aguardiente* is stylistically neutral in Spanish.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] However, *aguardiente* and *aguardente* are not legal denominations.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Instead, different categories of *aguardientes* (spirits in the English version) are established according to raw materials.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In the Spanish version, wine spirit (brandy) is *aguardiente de vino*, fruit spirit is *aguardiente de fruta*, grain spirit (other than whiskey and neutral grain spirit) is *aguardiente de cereales*, etc.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Some drinks named *aguardiente* or similar are of different origins (grape pomace, sugarcane); other drinks with the same origin may have different names (clairin, brandy).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Brazil, a beverage known as *cachaça* or *pinga*, considered distinct from traditional *aguardiente*, is made from sugarcane.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Cachaça* has two varieties: unaged (white) and aged (gold).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] White *cachaça* is usually bottled immediately after distillation and tends to be cheaper.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is often used to prepare caipirinha and other beverages in which *cachaça* is an ingredient.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Dark *cachaça*, usually seen as the "premium" variety, is aged in wood barrels and is meant to be drunk neat.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Traditionally, no herbs are used to flavor the *cachaça*; its flavor is influenced by the fermentation agent, time spent in the cask, or the type of wood from which the barrel is made.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] One form that can be qualified as moonshine is known as "Maria Louca" ("Crazy Mary").
[src:acerum/aguardiente] This is *aguardiente*, made in jails by inmates.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It can be made from many cereals, ranging from beans to rice, or whatever can be converted into alcohol, be it fruit peels or candy, using improvised and illegal equipment.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Grogue, also known as grogu or grogo (derived from English grog), is a Cape Verdean alcoholic beverage, an *aguardiente* made from sugarcane processed in a trapiche.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Its production is fundamentally artisanal, and nearly all the sugarcane is used in producing grogue.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Chile, *aguardiente* is an alcoholic beverage of 45% and higher ABV (beverages with over 55% ABV are illegal).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is made, like Italian grappa, by distilling the grape residue, primarily the skins and pulp (**hollejo**) plus the stems (**escobajos**) and seeds, left over from winemaking after pressing the grapes.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is used to make several other flavored liquors, such as the *murtado* or **enmurtillado** (using sun-dried *murtilla*, an orange-reddish wild rose fruit), the **enguindado** (soaking sun-dried morello cherries) and *licor de oro* (flavored with saffron and lemon peel).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Dried mint, peeled walnuts, almonds, and other aromatic herbs are also used to flavor the *aguardiente*.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is mainly consumed by itself or as a base to make *cola de mono* ("monkey tail").
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Colombia, *aguardiente* is an anise-flavored liqueur derived from sugarcane, popular in the Andean region.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Different flavors are obtained by adding different amounts of aniseed, leading to extensive marketing and fierce competition between brands.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Aguardiente* has 24%–29% alcohol content.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Other anise-flavored liqueurs similar to *aguardiente*, but with a lower alcohol content, are also sold.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Since the Spanish era, *aguardiente* has maintained the status of the most popular alcoholic beverage in the Andean regions of Colombia, with the notable exception of the Caribbean region, where rum is most popular.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Generally, *aguardiente* is rarely drunk in cocktails and usually drunk neat.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] On the Caribbean coast, there is a moonshine called "Cococho", an *aguardiente* infamous for the number of blindness cases due to the addition of methanol.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Costa Rica, it is 30% alcohol, with a neutral flavor.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The Costa Rican government tightly controls Guaro to help prevent clandestine production.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Guam and the Mariana Islands, a distilled version of *tubâ* (coconut palm wine introduced from the Philippines) is known as *aguajente* (also *aguayente* or *agi*).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It was prevalent among the Chamorro people, but is largely extinct; the United States banned its manufacture soon after the acquisition of Guam from the Spanish Empire in 1899.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] A local company "Aguayente distillers" has recently installed a commercial still and will soon start distilling liquor from locally grown potatoes.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is also derived from sugar cane, but unlike Colombia, it is left largely unflavoured.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is then taken straight as shots, mulled with cinnamon (*canela* in Spanish) and fruit juices to make the hot cocktail *canelazo*, or mixed with the juice of naranjilla and spices for the hot cocktail *draquita*.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Locally or artisanally made *aguardiente* is commonly called *punta*, "puro" or *trago*, and alcohol content can vary widely, from "mild" *puntas* of about 10% to "strong" of about 40% or higher.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The traditional distillation process produces *aguardiente* as strong as 60 g/L.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Every Ecuadorian province has a slightly different flavor to the *aguardiente* made there, and each province has a different recipe for *canelazo*.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Ecuador, *aguardiente* is the most commonly consumed strong alcohol.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Mexico, *aguardiente* goes by many names, including *habanero*.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In the state of Michoacán, *charanda* is a traditional rum-like sugar cane *aguardiente*.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Casa Berreteaga marketed an *aguardiente* called "Berreteaga", which used sugarcane sourced from the Coxcatlan region of Puebla.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Berreteaga was a fortified wine made from rum and sweet wine (usually Muscat) or (uncommonly) a sweet brandy that was then aged in oak barrels.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Portuguese *aguardente* has several varieties.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Aguardente vínica* is distilled from either good quality or undrinkable wine.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is mostly used to fortify wines such as port or aged to make *aguardente velha* (old burning water), a kind of brandy.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Aguardente bagaceira* (mostly known as "bagaço") is made from pomace to prevent waste after the close of wine season.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is usually bootlegged, as most drinkers only appreciate it in its traditional formulation of 50% to 80% ABV.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] A common way to drink it is as *café com cheirinho* ("coffee with a little scent"), a liqueur coffee made with espresso.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In the Azores, this *espresso-aguardente* combination is commonly referred to as *café com música* ("coffee with music").
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Aguardente Medronho* is a variety distilled from the fruit of the *Arbutus unedo* tree.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In Madeira, it is the core ingredient for *poncha*, a beverage around which a festival is based.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Most of the *aguardente* from the region is made from sugarcane.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In certain areas of the Pyrenees in Catalonia, *aiguardent*, as it is known in Catalan, is used as an essential ingredient in the preparation of *tupí*, a type of cheese.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Galicia is renowned for the quality and variety of its *augardentes* (Galician), or *aguardientes* (Spanish), including *augardente de bagazo* (*aguardiente de Orujo*), which is obtained from the distillation of the pomace of grapes, and is clear and colorless.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It typically contains over 50% alcohol, sometimes significantly more, and is still made traditionally in many villages across Galicia today.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Augardente de herbas*, usually yellow, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo* and herbs (*herbas*), with chamomile being a substantial ingredient.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Licor café* (typical distilled drink in the province of Ourense), black in color, is a sweet liqueur made with *augardente de bagazo*, coffee (*café*), and sugar.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] *Crema de augardente* or c*rema de caña* is a cream liqueur based on *augardente*, coffee, cream, milk, and other ingredients.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] In some places in Galicia, a small glass is traditionally taken at breakfast as a tonic before a hard day's work on the land.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The word "*orujo*" is Spanish and not Galician, but is used to distinguish Galician and some Spanish augardentes from those of other countries.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Most of the moonshine in Spain is made as a byproduct of winemaking by distilling the squeezed skins of the grapes.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The essential product is called "*orujo*" or "*aguardiente*" (burning water).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] The homemade versions are usually more potent and have a higher alcoholic content, well over the 40% that the commercial versions typically have.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It is often mixed with herbs, spices, fruits, or other distillates.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] Types include *pacharán*, *licor de café* and *orujo de hierbas* (tea mixed with orujo).
[src:acerum/aguardiente] During the mission and rancho periods of California history, *aguardiente* was made out of mission grapes.
[src:acerum/aguardiente] It was popular during the Gold Rush of 1849.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The word *aquavit* derives from the Latin *aqua vitae*, "water of life." Compare the words *whisky* and *whiskey*, from Gaelic *uisce beatha*, which has the same meaning.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Likewise, clear fruit brandy is called *eau de vie* (French for "water of life").
[src:acerum/akvavit] Akvavit is an important part of Nordic drinking culture, where it is often drunk during festive gatherings, such as Christmas dinners and the Midsummer celebration, and as an aperitif.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Iceland, Sweden, Denmark, and Germany, aquavit is chilled and often drunk in a single gulp from a small shot glass.
[src:acerum/akvavit] This is usually attributed to tradition.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Norway, it is not generally chilled, but enjoyed slowly.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Sweden, aquavit is commonly consumed immediately following a song, called a snapsvisa.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The most well-known song is "Helan Går".
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Finland and Sweden, aquavit consumed from a shot glass is also commonly associated with crayfish parties, which are traditionally held during late August.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Denmark, aquavit is called snaps or akvavit, and is primarily consumed in December during Christmas lunches or around Easter during Easter lunches.
[src:acerum/akvavit] It is consumed year-round, though, mainly for lunches of traditional Danish dishes where beer is also always on the table.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Norway, where most aquavit is matured in oak casks, the drink is served at room temperature in tulip-shaped glasses.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Aquavit arguably complements beer well, and its consumption is very often preceded by a swig of beer.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Akvavit must be distilled from an agricultural base, most commonly grain or potatoes.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Similarly to gin, it is flavoured with botanicals.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The dominant flavours must be caraway or dill, or sometimes both.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Swedish Akvavit must also contain fennel in order to be labelled as such.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Other common botanicals include cardamom, cumin, anise, and coriander.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The Danish distillery Aalborg makes an akvavit distilled with amber, which imparts a pine-like citrusy note.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The Aalborg brand is now produced in Norway by Arcus Group.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The recipes and flavours differ between brands, with each brand's unique characteristics coming from distillation methods and supporting botanicals in their blends.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Un-aged Akvavit is clear, while aged Akvavit typically has a pale straw-to-golden hue, depending on how long it has been aged in oak casks (most common in Norway) or the amount of colourant used.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Normally, a darker colour suggests a higher age or the use of young casks, although artificial caramel colouring and infusing fruits or botanicals for colour and flavour are permitted before bottling.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Clear akvavit is often called *taffel*, meaning table aquavit.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Taffel aquavit is typically aged in old casks that do not colour the finished spirit, or it is not aged at all.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The earliest known reference to "aquavit" is found in a 1531 letter from the Lord of Bergenshus castle, (Norway) Eske Bille, to Olav Engelbrektsson, the last Roman Catholic Archbishop of Norway.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The letter, dated April 13 and accompanying a package, offers the archbishop "some water which is called Aqua Vite and is a help for all sort of illness which a man can have both internally and externally".
[src:acerum/akvavit] While this claim for the medicinal properties of the drink may be rather inflated, aquavit is popularly believed to ease the digestion of rich foods.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Norway, it is drunk at celebrations, particularly Christmas, Easter, or May 17 (Norwegian Constitution Day).
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Denmark, it is traditionally associated with Christmas and Easter lunches.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In Sweden, it is a staple of the traditional midsummer celebrations dinner, usually drunk while singing one of many drinking songs.
[src:acerum/akvavit] It is usually drunk as snaps during meals, especially during the appetizer course — along with pickled herring, crayfish, lutefisk, or smoked fish.
[src:acerum/akvavit] In this regard, it is popularly quipped that aquavit helps the fish swim down to the stomach.
[src:acerum/akvavit] It is also a regular in traditional Norwegian Christmas meals, including roasted rib of pork and rib of lamb (*pinnekjøtt*).
[src:acerum/akvavit] The spices and the alcohol are said to help digest the meal, which is very rich in fat.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Among the most important brands are Løiten, Lysholm, Opland, and Simers from Norway; Aalborg and Brøndum from Denmark; and O.P.
[src:acerum/akvavit] While the Danish and Swedish variants are normally very light in colour, most of the Norwegian brands are matured in oak casks for at least six months, and for some brands even as long as 12 years, making them generally darker in colour.
[src:acerum/akvavit] While members of all three nations can be found to claim that "their" style of aquavit is the best as a matter of national pride, Swedish *akvavit* is typically the most renowned around the world, specifically so in the culinary scene.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Whilst the Norwegian *akevitt* tends to have if not the most distinctive character, then at least the most overpowering flavour and deepest colour due to the aging process.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Peculiar to the Norwegian tradition are *Linje Aquavits* (such as "Løiten Linie" and "Lysholm Linie").
[src:acerum/akvavit] Linje Aquavit is named after the tradition of sending oak barrels of aquavit with ships from Norway to Australia and back again, thereby passing the equator ("linje") twice before being bottled.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The constant movement, high humidity, and fluctuating temperature cause the spirit to extract more flavour and contribute to accelerated maturation.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Norwegian aquavit distillers Anora (formerly Arcus) carried out a test where they tried to emulate the rocking of the casks aboard the "Linje" ships while the oak barrels were subjected to the weather elements, as they would aboard a ship.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The finished product was, according to Anora, far from the taste that a proper *linje* aquavit should have.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Therefore, to this day, boats loaded with "Linie Aquavit" set sail from Norway to Australia and back again before they are bottled and sold as part of the Norwegian Christmas traditions, but also enjoyed all year round.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Aquavit was seldom produced outside of the Nordic countries, but that began to change dramatically starting around 2010, especially in the United States, and particularly in areas that have larger concentrations of people with a Nordic heritage.
[src:acerum/akvavit] An exception, however, is Northern Germany, and in particular the German state of Schleswig-Holstein, which was part of Denmark until the 19th century (see History of Schleswig-Holstein) and still has a notable Danish minority.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Among the most important German brands are Bommerlunder from Flensburg, Kieler Sprotte from Kiel, and Malteserkreuz.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Malteserkreuz has been produced in Berlin since 1924 by a subsidiary of Sweden's Vin & Sprit AB (now Pernod Ricard), the producer of many Swedish akvavits, and can be considered a German imitation of the Nordic aquavits since it is based on an original Danish recipe.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Brands from Schleswig-Holstein, however, often have a long history, comparable to their Nordic counterparts.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Bommerlunder, for instance, has been made since 1760.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Aquavit is also an important part of the traditional cuisine of Schleswig-Holstein.
[src:acerum/akvavit] German aquavit is virtually always distilled from fermented grain and generally has an alcohol content of 38% by volume, marginally less than Scandinavian aquavits.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Many distilleries in the United States produce aquavit, especially in parts of the country with high populations of people of Nordic heritage.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Examples include Colorado, Minnesota, Michigan, Wisconsin, Montana, Illinois, Oregon, New Hampshire, and Washington.
[src:acerum/akvavit] The Midwest states in particular do quite well for the category and have produced numerous internationally acclaimed/award-winning brands.
[src:acerum/akvavit] See List of Akvavit Producers in the United States for brand names and distilleries.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Aquavit is also seeing a rise in popularity in Canada, particularly in Scandinavian settlements.
[src:acerum/akvavit] Notable brands include Spirit of York Co in Toronto, Ontario, Drum Distilling Co in Drumheller, Alberta, and The Newfoundland Distillery Co, in Clarkes Beach Newfoundland.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Humans have had interactions with alcohol for an extensive period of time.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some of the earliest evidence points back to our primate ancestors.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] One hypothesis known as the "drunken monkey" hypothesis proposes that these ancestors were more attracted to riper fruits due to their increased sugar and ethanol content which provided an energy efficient and nutritional substance for consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The earliest physical evidence of alcohol production and consumption by humans was discovered by a Stanford research team in 2018.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Near what is now known as Haifa, Israel, the research team discovered remnants of alcohol that ranged between 11,700-13,700 years old.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] More evidence of early human and alcohol interactions come from 7,000 B.C. in ancient China and 5,980 B.C. in Georgia.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] There are a variety of theories as to why humans began drinking alcohol in the first place.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some of those most prominent are due to its perceived nutritional value, medicinal abilities, as well as its ability to provide hydration when clean water wasn't readily available.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Because alcohol could provide these advantages, it started as a substance used to better and prolong the human life.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This provides a stark contrast to the unsafe way that some humans interact with alcohol today.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A standard drink is a measure of alcohol consumption representing a fixed amount of pure ethanol, used in relation to recommendations about alcohol consumption and its relative risks to health.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The size of a standard drink varies from 8g to 20g across countries, but 10g alcohol (12.7 milliliters) is used in the WHO Alcohol Use Disorders Identification Test (AUDIT)'s questionnaire form example, and has been adopted by more countries than any other amount.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The recommended maximum intake (or *safe limits*) of alcohol varies from no intake, to daily, weekly, or daily/weekly guidelines provided by health agencies of governments.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The WHO published a statement in *The Lancet Public Health* in April 2023 that *"there is no safe amount that does not affect health"*.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Department of Agriculture, based on NHANES 2013–2014 surveys, women in the US ages 20 and up consume on average 6.8 grams/day and men consume on average 15.5 grams/day.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A March 2023 review found light-moderate daily drinking not significantly associated with increased mortality rate, but higher intake raises risk, with women affected at lower levels than men.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, according to a 2024 systematic review and meta-analysis, even at 20 g/day (1 large beer), the risk of developing an alcohol use disorder (AUD) is nearly 3 times higher than non-drinkers, and the risk of dying from an AUD is about 2 times higher than non-drinkers.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] While the terms "drug" and "medicine" are sometimes used interchangeably, "drug" can have a negative connotation, often associated with illegal substances like cocaine or heroin.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The term narcotic usually refers to opiates or opioids, which are called narcotic analgesics.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In common parlance and legal usage, it is often used imprecisely to mean illicit drugs, irrespective of their pharmacology.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, in countries with alcohol prohibition, it is classified and treated as a narcotic.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Also, research acknowledges that alcohol can have similar effects to narcotics in head and/or trunk trauma situations.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In addition to these findings, recent research indicates that among chronic pain patients on long-term opioid therapy, alcohol consumption is connected to heightened opioid cravings.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The normalization of alcohol consumption, along with past misconceptions about its health benefits, also promoted by the industry, further reinforces the mistaken idea that it is not a "drug".
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Even within the realm of scientific inquiry, the common phrase "drugs and alcohol" persists, implying that alcohol is somehow separate from other drugs.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Criticism of the alcohol industry may note that the industry argues that "alcohol is not a drug".
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Also, some religious organizations, such as the Catholic Church, requires alcoholic sacramental wine in the Eucharist and do not explicitly categorize alcohol as a "drug" in the same manner as illicit substances.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This practice has been a longstanding tradition within the Church, reflecting its historical, theological significance, and normalization of alcohol use within its rituals.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, the term "Alcohol and Other Drugs", a term frequently used by public health authorities, emphasizes this inclusion by grouping alcohol with other substances that alter mood and behavior.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Paradoxically, despite being legal, alcohol, scientifically classified as a drug, has demonstrably been linked to greater social harm than most illegal drugs.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This contradicts the perception some hold of alcohol being a harmless substance.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol consumption is fully legal and available in most countries of the world.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Home made alcoholic beverages with low alcohol content like wine, and beer is also legal in most countries, but distilling moonshine outside of a registered distillery remains illegal in most of them.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some majority-Muslim countries, such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Pakistan, Iran and Libya prohibit the production, sale, and consumption of alcoholic beverages because they are forbidden by Islam.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Laws banning alcohol consumption are found in some Indian states as well as some Native American reservations in the U.S.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In addition, there are regulations on alcohol sales and use in many countries throughout the world.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] For instance, the majority of countries have a minimum legal drinking age to purchase or consume alcoholic beverages, although there are often exceptions such as underage consumption of small amounts of alcohol with parental supervision.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Also, some countries have bans on public intoxication.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking while driving or intoxicated driving is frequently outlawed and it may be illegal to have an open container of alcohol or liquor bottle in an automobile, bus or aircraft.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In Iran, consumption of alcohol (one glass) is punished by 80 lashes, but repeated offenses may lead to death penalty, although rarely exercised.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In 2012, two men were sentenced to death after a third offense in Khorasan.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The "R" in WHO's SAFER initiative stands for "Raise prices on alcohol through excise taxes and pricing policies," emphasizing the importance of economic measures to mitigate alcohol-related harm.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The Alcohol (Minimum Pricing) (Scotland) Act 2012 is an Act of the Scottish Parliament, which introduces a statutory minimum price for alcohol, initially 50p per unit, as an element in the program to counter alcohol problems.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The Liquor Act 2019 is an act enacted and signed into legislation by the Northern Territory Legislative Assembly in 2019, which introduces a statutory minimum price for alcohol in order to counter alcohol problems.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The Public Health (Minimum Price for Alcohol) (Wales) Act 2018 (anaw 5) is an Act of the National Assembly for Wales, which introduces a statutory minimum price for alcohol, initially 50p per unit, as an element in the programme to counter alcohol problems.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Austria, Switzerland and Germany determine that a barkeeper has to offer one or more non-alcoholic beverages at a cheaper price than any alcoholic drink.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Before the so-called *Apfelsaft-Paragraph* (*apple* *juice clause*) was established in Germany in 2002 beer was often the cheapest beverage available.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol packaging warning messages (alcohol warning labels, AWLs) are warning messages that appear on the packaging of alcoholic drinks concerning their health effects.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol server training is a form of occupational education typically provided to servers, sellers and consumers of alcohol to prevent intoxication, drunk driving and underage drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This training is sometimes regulated and mandated by state and local laws, predominantly in North America, and increasingly in other English-speaking countries such as Australia.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In some places, such as Australia, gaining such qualifications is required by law, before one can work to sell alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some parents are willing to provide alcohol for their children if they drink it in a controlled environment.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Furnishing alcohol to one's own children is permitted in 31 states, while it's illegal to do so for other people's children in all fifty states.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, despite research indicating negative consequences, many parents mistakenly believe that providing alcohol to their underage children will protect them from drinking-related harm.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This misconception persists even though studies have shown a connection between parental alcohol supply and unfavorable outcomes related to alcohol consumption among minors.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Parental provision of alcohol during childhood may raise the risk of risky drinking in adolescence.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, methodological limitations hinder causal conclusions.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] To clarify this relationship, more robust longitudinal studies are needed that differentiate between sips and full drinks, accurately measure confounding factors, and apply multivariable adjustments.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Parental attitudes that are less restrictive regarding children's alcohol consumption are linked to an earlier onset of alcohol use, increased frequency of use, and higher instances of drunkenness among children.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Additionally, when children perceive their parents as having more lenient attitudes towards alcohol, they are more likely to engage in drinking themselves.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Adolescents permitted to drink by their parents were more likely to quickly move from their first drink to binge drinking (5 or more drinks at once) and heavy drinking (3 or more times in the past year).
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] These findings contradict the belief that parental approval of underage drinking protects against alcohol misuse, highlighting the risks associated with adolescent heavy drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Parents may face significant legal consequences in various countries and jurisdictions if they knowingly allow their children to drink alcohol without supervision.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This liability arises from a perceived failure to protect the child from the risks associated with alcohol consumption, which could lead to investigations by child protective services.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 3 is part of "The Alcohol Policy Playbook," which is a resource for reaching the goals of the WHO European Framework for Action on Alcohol (2022–2025) and the WHO Global Alcohol Action Plan (2022–2030).
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The Global Information System on Alcohol and Health (GISAH) is a tool developed by the WHO to collect and analyze data on alcohol consumption, related health issues, and policy responses in countries.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The WHO's SAFER initiative aims to reduce alcohol-related harm through a comprehensive set of strategies.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In October 2024, the WHO Regional Office for Europe launched the "Redefine alcohol" campaign to address alcohol-related health risks, as alcohol causes nearly 1 in 11 deaths in the region.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The campaign aims to raise awareness about alcohol's link to over 200 diseases, including several cancers, and to encourage healthier choices by sharing research and personal stories.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] It also calls for stricter regulation of alcohol to reduce its societal harm.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This initiative is part of the WHO/EU Evidence into Action Alcohol Project, which seeks to reduce alcohol-related harm across Europe.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2019 survey conducted by the American Institute for Cancer Research (AICR) showed that only 45% of Americans were aware of the associated risk of cancer due to alcohol consumption, up from 39% in 2017.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The AICR believes that alcohol advertising about the healthy cardiovascular benefits of modest alcohol overshadow messages about the increased cancer risks.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The alcohol industry has tried to market its products to appeal to impressionable youth and young adults.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking alcoholic beverages increase the risk for breast cancer.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Several studies indicate that the use of marketing by the alcohol industry to associate their products with breast cancer awareness campaigns, known as pinkwashing, is misleading and potentially harmful.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol industries have marketed products directly to the LGBT+ community.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In 2010, of the sampled parades that listed sponsors, 61% of the prides were sponsored by the alcohol industry.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A study found that alcohol consumption within LGBTQ+ communities presents a challenge for health promotion efforts.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The positive association with alcohol within these communities makes it harder to reduce alcohol-related health issues.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Teetotalism is the practice of never consuming alcohol, specifically in alcoholic drinks.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A person who practices (and possibly advocates) teetotalism is called a teetotaler (US) or teetotaller (UK), or said to be teetotal.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Globally, in 2016, 57% of adults did not drink alcohol in the past 12 months, and 44.5% had never consumed alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A number of temperance organizations have been founded in order to promote teetotalism and provide spaces for non-drinkers to socialize.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Intermittent sobriety refers to planned periods of abstinence from alcohol, often as part of awareness campaigns or personal health initiatives.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Sober curious is a recent cultural movement and lifestyle that focuses on consuming no or limited alcohol for wellness purposes.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The movement gained traction through the promotion by social media influencers.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] It differs from traditional abstinence in that it is not founded on asceticism, religious condemnation of alcohol or previous alcohol abuse, but motivated by a curiosity of a sober lifestyle.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Markets have reacted by offering a wider selection of non-alcoholic beverages.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Sober curiosity is often defined as having the option to question or change one's drinking habits, for mental or physical health reasons.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] It may be practiced in many ways, ranging from complete abstinence to more thought about when and how much is consumed.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Since the onset of the COVID-19 pandemic, more people in Europe have reduced their alcohol consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking alcohol is generally socially acceptable and is legal in most countries, unlike with many other recreational substances.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Many students attending colleges, universities, and other higher education institutions consume alcoholic beverages.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, there are often restrictions on alcohol sale and use, for instance a minimum age for drinking and laws against public drinking and drinking and driving.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2024 meta-analysis found that alcohol consumption increased on average each year, with the most significant rise occurring between the ages of 12 and 13.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking peaked around 22 years old, then began to decline at 24.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol holds considerable societal and cultural significance, playing a role in social interactions across much of the world.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking establishments, such as bars and nightclubs, revolve primarily around the sale and consumption of alcoholic beverages, and parties, festivals, and social gatherings commonly involve alcohol consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol is related to various societal problems, including drunk driving, accidental injuries, sexual assaults, domestic abuse, and violent crime.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol remains illegal for sale and consumption in a number of countries, mainly in the Middle East.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Research on the societal benefits of alcohol is rare, but a 2017 study suggested there it was beneficial.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol is often used as a social lubricant; it increases occurrences of Duchenne smiling, talking, and social bonding, even when participants are unaware of their alcohol consumption or lack thereof.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In a study of the UK, regular drinking was correlated with happiness, feeling that life was worthwhile, and life satisfaction.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] According to a causal path analysis the cause was vice versa; alcohol consumption was not the cause, but rather that the life satisfaction resulted in greater happiness and an inclination to visit pubs and develop a regular drinking venue.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] City centre bars were distinguished by their focus on maximizing alcohol sales.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Community pubs had less variation in visible group sizes and longer, more focused conversations than those in city centre bars.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking regularly at a community pub led to higher trust in others and better networking with the local community, compared to non-drinkers and city centre bar drinkers.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drinking games are popular social activities, particularly among young adults and college students, but they come with significant health risks.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol in association football has long been a complex issue, with significant cultural and behavioral implications.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Football is widely observed in various settings such as television broadcasts, sports bars, and arenas, contributing to the drinking culture surrounding the sport.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2007 study at the University of Texas at Austin monitored the drinking habits of 541 students over two football seasons.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] It revealed that high-profile game days ranked among the heaviest drinking occasions, similar to New Year's Eve.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Male students increased their consumption for all games, while socially active female students drank heavily during away games.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Lighter drinkers also showed a higher likelihood of risky behaviors during away games as their intoxication increased.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This research highlights specific drinking patterns linked to collegiate sports events.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Overwork is linked to an increased risk of unhealthy alcohol consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Also, unemployment can heighten the risk of alcohol consumption and smoking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] As many as 15% of employees show problematic alcohol-related behaviors in the workplace, such as drinking before going to work or even drinking on the job.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In order to understand all the implications that alcohol has on society, it is important that the effects of alcohol are understood at the neurological level.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] While the process of absorbing alcohol involves the entire body, the brain is especially impacted.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In general, the brain's communication pathways and information processing are greatly altered when alcohol is in the human body.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] How much the brain is effected depends upon blood alcohol content (BAC).
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] When someone has a minimal to moderate BAC, symptoms can include feelings of euphoria, excitement, and confusion, impaired motor skills, impaired judgement, nausea, and memory loss.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] When one has a severe BAC level, they are at risk of injury, suffocation, coma, and death.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol can result in irreversible damage when consumption is severe enough.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] While alcohol can provide a feeling of relief from the stressors occurring in one's life, it's important to note that this relief is temporary.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The urge to make this feeling of relief constant in one's life can lead to an addiction cycle that is similar to other forms of drug use which includes intoxication, withdrawal, and anticipation.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some studies have made a connection between hookup culture and substance use.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Most students said that their hookups occurred after drinking alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Frietas stated that in her study, the relationships between drinking and the party scene and between alcohol and hookup culture were "impossible to miss".
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Studies suggest that the degree of alcoholic intoxication in young people directly correlates with the level of risky behavior, such as engaging in multiple sex partners.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In 2018, the first study of its kind, found that alcohol and caffeinated energy drinks is linked with casual, risky sex among college-age adults.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol intoxication is associated with an increased risk that people will become involved in risky sexual behaviors, such as unprotected sex.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Both men, and women, reported higher intentions to avoid using a condom when they were intoxicated by alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Women with unintended pregnancies are more likely to smoke tobacco, drink alcohol during pregnancy, and binge drink during pregnancy, which results in poorer health outcomes.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The relationship between drinking alcohol and how HIV develops and progresses in people has been the subject of prior research investigations.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] To date, HIV has been recognized as an alcohol-attributable STI in the WHO's most recent comparative risk assessment or related exercises.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol may cause hurtful communication.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drunk dialing refers to an intoxicated person making phone calls that they would not likely make if sober, often a lonely individual calling former or current love interests.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2021 study that examined the relationship between drunk texting and emotional dysregulation found a positive correlation.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The findings suggest that interventions targeting emotional regulation skills may be beneficial.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol-related crime refers to criminal activities that involve alcohol use as well as violations of regulations covering the sale or use of alcohol; in other words, activities violating the alcohol laws.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some crimes are uniquely tied to alcohol, such as public intoxication or underage drinking, while others are simply more likely to occur together with alcohol consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Underage drinking and drunk driving are the most prevalent alcohol-specific offenses in the United States and a major problem in many, if not most, countries worldwide.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Similarly, about one-third of arrests in the United States involve alcohol misuse, and arrests for alcohol-related crimes constitute a high proportion of all arrests made by police in the US and elsewhere.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Binge drinking is a style of drinking that is popular in several countries worldwide, and overlaps somewhat with social drinking since it is often done in groups.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The degree of intoxication however, varies between and within various cultures that engage in this practice.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A binge on alcohol can occur over hours, last up to several days, or in the event of extended abuse, even weeks.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Due to the long term effects of alcohol abuse, binge drinking is considered to be a major public health issue.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Binge drinking is more common in males, during adolescence and young adulthood.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Heavy regular binge drinking is associated with adverse effects on neurologic, cardiac, gastrointestinal, hematologic, immune, and musculoskeletal organ systems as well as increasing the risk of alcohol induced psychiatric disorders.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A US-based review of the literature found that up to one-third of adolescents binge-drink, with 6% reaching the threshold of having an alcohol-related substance use disorder.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Approximately one in 25 women binge-drinks during pregnancy, which can lead to fetal alcohol syndrome and fetal alcohol spectrum disorders.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Binge drinking during adolescence is associated with traffic accidents and other types of accidents, violent behavior as well as suicide.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The more often a child or adolescent binge drinks and the younger they are the more likely that they will develop an alcohol use disorder including alcoholism.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A large number of adolescents who binge-drink also consume other psychotropic substances.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol causes a plethora of detrimental effects in society.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2023 systematic review estimated the societal costs of alcohol use to be around 2.6% of the GDP.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Many emergency room visits involve alcohol use.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol availability and consumption rates and alcohol rates are positively associated with nuisance, loitering, panhandling, and disorderly conduct in public space.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2011 study challenged the perception of heroin as the more dangerous substance.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The research suggests, when considering the wider social, physical, and financial costs, alcohol may be more harmful.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Individuals who engage with or share alcohol-related content on social networking services tend to exhibit higher levels of alcohol use and related issues.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Varying trends of alcohol use can be correlated to certain racial groups and ethnicities.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] For example, compared to other racial and ethic groups, White Americans and Native Americans have a higher risk of developing alcohol use disorders.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Specifically for Native Americans, 11.7% of all deaths are related to alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] By comparison, about 5.9% of global deaths are attributable to alcohol consumption.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Additionally, Hispanic Americans are the least likely to receive treatment for alcohol use disorders in the United States.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The differences in alcohol use and many other types of substance use among racial groups and ethnicities can often be attributed to systemic issues involving negative stereotypes and biases based on race.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Gaps in alcohol use based on gender exist everywhere.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] These gaps can vary depending on different countries and cultures.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] On a global level, alcohol consumption is typically an activity that's dominated by men.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This trend also exists in the United States.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] On average, men consume three times the amount of alcohol that women do.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Men also face more alcohol related harm than women do such as injury and death.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] One possible explanation for this increased consumption is due to the fact that women are affected by smaller amounts of alcohol compared to men which could cause them to consume less of it.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Another explanation for these differences is varying societal standards that are associated with drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In the United States, there are increased feelings of disapproval associated with heavy drinkers that are women than are men.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] It's important to note that these trends are subject to change.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Recent data from a study done in 2021 from the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism found that women were binge-drinking more than men for the first time in history.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The relationship between religion and alcohol exhibits variations across cultures, geographical areas, and religious denominations.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some religions emphasize moderation and responsible use as a means of honoring the divine gift of life, while others impose outright bans on alcohol as a means of honoring the divine gift of life.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Moreover, within the same religious tradition, there are many adherents that may interpret and practice their faith's teachings on alcohol in diverse ways.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Hence, a wide range of factors, such as religious affiliation, levels of religiosity, cultural traditions, family influences, and peer networks, collectively influence the dynamics of this relationship.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In some cultures, including those with religious traditions, consuming alcohol in moderation to celebrate joyful occasions is accepted in a non-religious, secular context.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] During the Jewish holiday of Purim, Jews are obligated to drink (especially Kosher wine) until their judgmental abilities become impaired according to the Book of Esther.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] However, Purim has more of a national than a religious character.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The laws and social culture around this practice vary by country and institution type, and within an institution, some students may drink heavily whereas others may not drink at all.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In the United States, drinking tends to be particularly associated with fraternities.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] List of hazing deaths in the United States highlights a troubling trend, as there has been at least one university hazing death each year from 1969 to 2021.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Over 200 university hazing deaths have occurred since 1838, with 40 deaths between 2007 and 2017 alone.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol poisoning is the biggest cause of death.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol abuse among college students refers to unhealthy alcohol drinking behaviors by college and university students.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] While the legal drinking age varies by country, the high number of underage students that consume alcohol has presented many problems and consequences for universities.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The causes of alcohol abuse tend to be peer pressure, fraternity or sorority involvement, and stress.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] College students who abuse alcohol can suffer from health concerns, poor academic performance or legal consequences.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Prevention and treatment include campus counseling, stronger enforcement of underage drinking or changing the campus culture.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Recent research indicates that the abundance of alcohol retailers and the availability of inexpensive alcoholic beverages are linked to heavy alcohol consumption among college students.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Research shows that people who are part of the LGBTQ+ community typically have higher rates of alcohol consumption compared to the general population.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] For example, a study completed in 2018 found that alcohol use in gay, lesbian, and bisexual people ages 18–25 was 64.3% which was 9.2% higher than the alcohol use of the general population.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Other studies show many similar findings in other LGBTQ+ populations across the world.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Additionally, the alcohol industries have marketed products directly to the LGBT+ community.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Research has shown that various psychosocial factors can influence alcohol consumption patterns throughout an individual's life.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2024 study from UT Southwestern Medical Center indicates that higher IQ during high school is linked to a greater likelihood of moderate or heavy drinking in midlife, with each one-point increase in IQ correlating to a 1.7% higher probability of such drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The study also found that this relationship is influenced by psychosocial factors, particularly income and career stress, highlighting the need for further research in diverse populations.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In emotional self-regulation, some people turn to drugs such as alcohol.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Drug use, an example of response modulation, can be used to alter emotion-associated physiological responses.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] For example, alcohol can produce sedative and anxiolytic effects.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A 2013 study found that immature defense mechanisms are linked to placing a higher value on junk food, alcohol, and television.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] There is a two-way street between loneliness and drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] People who drink more than once a week tend to feel lonelier, according to a study on Japanese workers during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] On the other hand, feelings of loneliness can also lead people to drink more, as shown in a separate study.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Loneliness is a major risk factor for depression and alcoholism.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Conditions such as alcoholism and mental illness are often associated with homelessness.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] For people in Russia, especially the youth, alcohol, and substance use is a major cause and reason for becoming and continuing to be homeless.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Also, street children from areas with limited resources have reported a high lifetime prevalence of substance use.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] The most commonly used substances are inhalants, followed by tobacco, alcohol, and marijuana.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Most people are under the influence of sedative-hypnotic drugs (such as alcohol or benzodiazepines) when they die by suicide, with alcoholism present in between 15% and 61% of cases.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Countries that have higher rates of alcohol use and a greater density of bars generally also have higher rates of suicide.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] About 2.2–3.4% of those who have been treated for alcoholism at some point in their life die by suicide.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcoholics who attempt suicide are usually male, older, and have tried to take their own lives in the past.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In adolescents who misuse alcohol, neurological and psychological dysfunctions may contribute to the increased risk of suicide.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A bargirl is a woman who is paid to entertain patrons in a bar or nightclub.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] A bar fine is a payment made by a customer to the operators of a bar or nightclub in East and Southeast Asia, allowing her to leave work early, typically to accompany a customer outside for sexual services.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Female sex workers in low- and middle-income countries have high rates of harmful alcohol use, which is associated with increased risk of risky sexual behavior.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Screening carried out in the 1990s in Malawi, an African country, indicated that about 80 per cent of bargirls carried the HIV virus.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Research carried out at the time indicated that economic necessity was a major consideration in engaging and persisting in sex work.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Various studies show a relationship between higher rates of alcohol consumption with people who have lower socioeconomic standings.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] People with low socioeconomic standings are also more likely to experience health complications due to alcohol use than people with high socioeconomic standings.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alcohol consumption can contribute to secondary poverty (where people fall back into poverty after escaping it).
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Some popular tourist destinations, are cracking down on the impacts of tourism from excessive drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] In an effort to promote a more sustainable tourism industry, these locations are implementing new regulations to curb binge drinking.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This includes Llucmajor, Palma, Calvia (Magaluf) in Majorca and Sant Antoni in Ibiza, where late-night sales of alcohol will be banned.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] This comes after years of issues with rowdy tourists and the negative impacts it has on local residents.
[src:acerum/alcohol-industry] Alternative methods of alcohol administration like alcohol enema, alcohol inhalation, vodka eyeballing, or using alcohol powder (which can be added to water to make an alcoholic beverage, or inhaled with a nebulizer), all carry significant health risks.
